The 3 new APIs are used to enable/disable/check the usage of `tf.random.Generator`, which will be the new backend for all the RNG in Keras. We plan to switch on the new code path by default in tf 2.8, and the behavior change will like to cause some breakage on user side (eg if the test is checking against some golden nubmer). These 3 APIs will allow user to disable and switch back to legacy behavior if they prefer. In future (eg tf 2.10), we expect to totally remove the legacy code path (stateful random Ops), and these 3 APIs will be removed as well.

Bounded dynamic dimensions may have size one at runtime and therefore the rank of the output is not known at the compile time. XLA doesn't support shapes with unknown rank so we need to reject such inputs.

Originally the kernel would have been implemented assuming the static input shapes and wasn't updated with bounded dynamic shapes.

Change-Id: Ie96925327e8f91cd973751a599f18af66636adcd","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/smalltalkman/tensorflow/commits/005ddfe4a123d7471030065f73d4fade10cc2775"},{"sha":"41ad65049b13213b6119b7d07a264e2b2661c72b","author":{"email":"d2f798c68dab979d539dfeddebc6b96a78f505a8@google.com","name":"Edward Schwartz"},"message":"Add caution to math.unsorted_segment_* documentation about bad segment_ids on GPU

In `tf.math`, `unsorted_segment_max`, `unsorted_segment_mean`, `unsorted_segment_min`, `unsorted_segment_prod`, `unsorted_segment_sqrt_n` and `unsorted_segment_sum` all expect that `segments_ids` are less than `num_segments`. On CPU, these are validated, and an error is thrown for out-of-bounds indices. [{"sha":"41ad65049b13213b6119b7d07a264e2b2661c72b","author":{"email":"d2f798c68dab979d539dfeddebc6b96a78f505a8@google.com","name":"Edward Schwartz"},"message":"Add caution to math.unsorted_segment_* documentation about bad segment_ids on GPU

In `tf.math`, `unsorted_segment_max`, `unsorted_segment_mean`, `unsorted_segment_min`, `unsorted_segment_prod`, `unsorted_segment_sqrt_n` and `unsorted_segment_sum` all expect that `segments_ids` are less than `num_segments`. On CPU, these are validated, and an error is thrown for out-of-bounds indices. On Gpu, these are NOT validated, and out-of-bound indices do not throw an error but instead result in safe but unspecified behavior.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 414688389
Change-Id: I5fe2351dbb6046dc69dfdf208610f1de8eda1eef","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Intel-tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/9ee0a7d858431c52a03883f038a84d351d60d742"},{"sha":"d9b47d5722fc08c5d06afba9f63177de266801f5","author":{"email":"a33a2701f6790f0a44360bcc1a194138e928e0d3@google.com","name":"Alexander Belyaev"},"message":"[tfrt:jit] Remove padding pass from TF CPURT.

There are several reasons to do that.
1. It is currently not used.
2. It does not improve the benchmarks if we disable peeling and in some cases
makes them worse.
3. It is not clear what padding value to select if we are doing padding of the
whole body of `linalg.tiled_loop`. For example, if we are padding a
`linalg.generic` that models a reduction, we might extract the padding value
from the `linalg.fill` that produces the output tensor for the reduction. For
other cases, we would need to write a giant switch-statement that would return
a padding value depending on what ops we have in `linalg.generic`. There is
another approach to that, which is being explored by gysit and nicolasvasilache: tile and pad a
single linalg.generic:

%input = input_op %input_of_input
loop
  %slice = extract_slice %input
  %pad = pad %slice %some_value_depending_on_the_generic_below
  %generic = linalg.generic %pad

and then fuse the input.

loop
  %slice = extract_slice %input_of_input
  %input = input_op %slice
  %pad = pad %slice with %some_value_depending_on_the_generic_below
  %generic = linalg.generic %pad

after that we have to move `pad` before `%input`:

loop
  %slice = extract_slice %input_of_input
  %pad = pad %slice with %previous_value_adjusted_depending_on_input_op
  %input = input_op %pad
  %generic = linalg.generic %pad

Gather op should get indices as constant and not as upper/lower bound as the default implementation does. Getting only the upper bound with fetch a particular value from data at the lowest or the highest index which is incorrect.

For example,

indices = sort([0, 1])

Getting the upper bound on indices will return [1, 1], making the gather result bound [2, 2] and not [3, 2].

Adds the concept of "plugins" to the inspected element payload. Also adds the first plugin, one that resolves StyleX atomic style names to their values and displays them as a unified style object (rather than a nested array of objects and booleans).

Source file names are displayed first, in dim color, followed by an ordered set of resolved style values.

For builds with the new feature flag disabled, there is no observable change.

version satisfies the given dependency range.

That way we don't forget to bump dependencies when we release a

Usually the build script updates transitive React dependencies so that
they refer to the corresponding release version.

For use-sync-external-store, though, we also want to support older
versions of React, too. So the normal behavior of the build script
isn't sufficient.

For now, to unblock, I hardcoded a special case, but we should consider

[{"sha":"53a37d7a5291d191a4d578e65b1983e304b6f834","author":{"email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com","name":"Smit Hinsu"},"message":"Fix Gather op bounds inference

Gather op should get indices as constant and not as upper/lower bound as the default implementation does. Getting only the upper bound with fetch a particular value from data at the lowest or the highest index which is incorrect.

For example,

data = [3, 2]
indices = sort([0, 1])

Getting the upper bound on indices will return [1, 1], making the gather result bound [2, 2] and not [3, 2].

Adds the concept of "plugins" to the inspected element payload. Also adds the first plugin, one that resolves StyleX atomic style names to their values and displays them as a unified style object (rather than a nested array of objects and booleans).

Source file names are displayed first, in dim color, followed by an ordered set of resolved style values.

For builds with the new feature flag disabled, there is no observable change.

A next step to build on top of this could be to make the style values editable, but change the logic such that editing one directly added an inline style to the item (rather than modifying the stylex class– which may be shared between multiple other components).","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/KimYangOfCat/react/commits/ad607469c58d337d23d05e3be73087d370f7d715"}]

Co-authored-by: Justus Hämäläinen <me@justushamalainen.fi>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/yyhaxx2108/react/commits/06a4615be28bc34f53ce1d9523995c83106b07e7"},{"sha":"25b18d31c8b7ffd256416672dc21c50dd22ac3dc","author":{"email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io","name":"Andrew Clark"},"message":"Traverse commit phase effects iteratively (#20094)

* Move traversal logic to ReactFiberCommitWork

The current traversal logic is spread between ReactFiberWorkLoop and
ReactFiberCommitWork, and it's a bit awkward, especially when
refactoring. Idk the ideal module structure, so for now I'd rather keep
it all in one file.

* Traverse commit phase effects iteratively

We suspect that using the JS stack to traverse through the tree in the
commit phase is slower than traversing iteratively.

I've kept the recursive implementation behind a flag, both so we have
the option to run an experiment comparing the two, and so we can revert
it easily later if needed.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/yyhaxx2108/react/commits/25b18d31c8b7ffd256416672dc21c50dd22ac3dc"},{"sha":"779a472b0901b2d28e382f3850b2ad09a555b014","author":{"email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io","name":"Andrew Clark"},"message":"Prevent inlining into recursive commit functions (#20105)

Adds a bunch of no-inline directives to commit phase functions to
prevent them from being inlined into one of our recursive algorithms.

The motivation is to minimize the number of variables in the recursive
functions, since each one contributes to the size of the stack frame.

Theoretically, this could help the performance of both the recursive
and non-recursive (iterative) implementations of the commit phase,
since even the iterative implementation sometimes uses the JS stack.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/yyhaxx2108/react/commits/779a472b0901b2d28e382f3850b2ad09a555b014"},{"sha":"b6a750be3ca0fc4126ef018e205c951b890c1881","author":{"email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com","name":"Brian Vaughn"},"message":"Make DevTools Websocket retry delay configurable (#20107)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/yyhaxx2108/react/commits/b6a750be3ca0fc4126ef018e205c951b890c1881"},{"sha":"343d7a4a7eb621a31ba946309b557e0988be3a63","author":{"email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com","name":"Brian Vaughn"},"message":"Fast Refresh: Don't block DevTools commit hook (#20129)

In some scenarios (either timing dependent, or pre-FR compatible React versions) FR blocked calling the React DevTools commit hook. This PR adds a test and a fix for that.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/yyhaxx2108/react/commits/343d7a4a7eb621a31ba946309b557e0988be3a63"},{"sha":"ffd84233568fd9d277eaba7c01d53d516f6f132f","author":{"email":"8a279ae1320350359ecfec7a379763633f1edc4c@fb.com","name":"Sebastian Markbåge"},"message":"[Flight] Add support for Module References in transport protocol (#20121)

* Refactor Flight to require a module reference to be brand checked

This exposes a host environment (bundler) specific hook to check if an
object is a module reference. This will be used so that they can be passed
directly into Flight without needing additional wrapper objects.

* Emit module references as a special type of value

We already have JSON and errors as special types of "rows". This encodes
module references as a special type of row value. This was always the
intention because it allows those values to be emitted first in the stream
so that as a large models stream down, we can start preloading as early
as possible.

We preload the module when they resolve but we lazily require them as they
are referenced.

* Emit module references where ever they occur

This emits module references where ever they occur. In blocks or even
directly in elements.

* Don't special case the root row

I originally did this so that a simple stream is also just plain JSON.

However, since we might want to emit things like modules before the root
module in the stream, this gets unnecessarily complicated. We could add
this back as a special case if it's the first byte written but meh.

* Update the protocol

* Add test for using a module reference as a client component

* Relax element type check

Since Flight now accepts a module reference as returned by any bundler
system, depending on the renderer running. We need to drastically relax
the check to include all of them. We can add more as we discover them.

* Move flow annotation

Seems like our compiler is not happy with stripping this.

* Some bookkeeping bug

* Can't use the private field to check","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/yyhaxx2108/react/commits/ffd84233568fd9d277eaba7c01d53d516f6f132f"},{"sha":"39eb6d1765cad681dc78b8955c39ed819064e7b4","author":{"email":"8a279ae1320350359ecfec7a379763633f1edc4c@fb.com","name":"Sebastian Markbåge"},"message":"Rename (#20134)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/yyhaxx2108/react/commits/39eb6d1765cad681dc78b8955c39ed819064e7b4"},{"sha":"930ce7c15a50a8d67f24a0bd85ec0937bc84afd6","author":{"email":"8a279ae1320350359ecfec7a379763633f1edc4c@fb.com","name":"Sebastian Markbåge"},"message":"Allow values to be encoded by "reference" to a value rather than the value itself (#20136)

These references are currently transformed into React.lazy values. We can use these in
React positions like element type or node position.

The Eigen commit changes the visibility of the `Packet` type ( `Packet4h2`) for the `Eigen::half` datatype. Prior to the commit, `Packet` type is defined as `Packet4h2` during both the `host` and `device` compile phases of hipcc/nvcc. After the commit the `Packet` type is defined as `Eigen::half` (size == 2) in the `host` compile phase, and as `Packet4h2` (size == 8) in the device compile phase.

`struct AvgPoolMeanReducer` has a member of type `Packet`(https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/r2.7/tensorflow/core/kernels/eigen_pooling.h#L367), and hence its size will be different during the `host` compile phase and `device` compile phase. It also seems that the implementation of the `average pooling` op ( https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/r2.7/tensorflow/core/kernels/avgpooling_op.h#L34-L38 ) will result in a `struct AvgPoolMeanReducer` argument being passed across the `host` / `device` compile boundary (atleast for `hipcc`) and size mismatch between the two, leads to the subsequent segfault.

The fix here is to ensure the `Packet` has the same definitition for both the `host` and `device` compile phases. However changing the type `packetCount_` to `int` unconditionally leads to compile errors, because during the non-gpu / gcc compiles the code within the `!defined(__HIPCC__)` block gets activated, and hence the changes in this commit are guarded by `defined(__HIPCC__)`. Using `int` for `packetCount_` is ok because `PacketAcces`s is already set to `false` within (a different) `defined(__HIPCC__)` block.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/lipracer/tensorflow/commits/eae91a24e179bc4d279ef1fe86d6050f30154215"},{"sha":"9e2237ee604e8a86f379f2d2236f1772491812c8","author":{"email":"88687f8e9d306a57b2163982d4c8fc9f4a2c5ea6@gmail.com","name":"Jacky_Yin"},"message":"fix: GIT_REPOSITORY for eigen

In `tf.math`, `unsorted_segment_max`, `unsorted_segment_mean`, `unsorted_segment_min`, `unsorted_segment_prod`, `unsorted_segment_sqrt_n` and `unsorted_segment_sum` all expect that `segments_ids` are less than `num_segments`. On CPU, these are validated, and an error is thrown for out-of-bounds indices. On Gpu, these are NOT validated, and out-of-bound indices do not throw an error but instead result in safe but unspecified behavior.

[{"sha":"ad607469c58d337d23d05e3be73087d370f7d715","author":{"email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com","name":"Brian Vaughn"},"message":"StyleX plug-in for resolving atomic styles to values for props.xstyle (#22808)

Adds the concept of "plugins" to the inspected element payload. Also adds the first plugin, one that resolves StyleX atomic style names to their values and displays them as a unified style object (rather than a nested array of objects and booleans).

Source file names are displayed first, in dim color, followed by an ordered set of resolved style values.

For builds with the new feature flag disabled, there is no observable change.

A next step to build on top of this could be to make the style values editable, but change the logic such that editing one directly added an inline style to the item (rather than modifying the stylex class– which may be shared between multiple other components).","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sanketshah19/react/commits/ad607469c58d337d23d05e3be73087d370f7d715"}]

[{"sha":"ad607469c58d337d23d05e3be73087d370f7d715","author":{"email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com","name":"Brian Vaughn"},"message":"StyleX plug-in for resolving atomic styles to values for props.xstyle (#22808)

Adds the concept of "plugins" to the inspected element payload. Also adds the first plugin, one that resolves StyleX atomic style names to their values and displays them as a unified style object (rather than a nested array of objects and booleans).

Source file names are displayed first, in dim color, followed by an ordered set of resolved style values.

For builds with the new feature flag disabled, there is no observable change.

A next step to build on top of this could be to make the style values editable, but change the logic such that editing one directly added an inline style to the item (rather than modifying the stylex class– which may be shared between multiple other components).","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/facebook/react/commits/ad607469c58d337d23d05e3be73087d370f7d715"}]

[{"sha":"93661bf16504b2a0c659f516df2212e9e01bd4b3","author":{"email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com","name":"Smit Hinsu"},"message":"Reject input with dynamic shapes in Squeeze xla op kernel

Bounded dynamic dimensions may have size one at runtime and therefore the rank of the output is not known at the compile time. XLA doesn't support shapes with unknown rank so we need to reject such inputs.

Originally the kernel would have been implemented assuming the static input shapes and wasn't updated with bounded dynamic shapes.

cty: The documented definition and comparison logic of cty.Number is now
refined to acknowledge that its true range is limited only to values
that have both a binary floating point and decimal representation,
because cty values are primarily designed to traverse JSON serialization
where numbers are always defined as decimal strings.

In particular, that means that two cty.Number values now always compare
as equal if their representation in JSON (under cty's own JSON encoder)
would be equal, even though the decimal approximation we use for that
conversion is slightly lossy. This pragmatic compromise avoids confusing
situations where a round-trip through JSON serialization (or other
serializations that use the same number format) may produce a value that
doesn't compare equal to the original.

This new definition of equals should not cause any significant behavior

We have a few dependencies that are such a significant part of Terraform's
behavior that they will often be the root cause of or the solution to a
bug reported against Terraform.

As a small quality-of-life improvement to help with diagnosing those,
we'll now report the selected versions for each of these so-called
"interesting" dependencies as part of our initial trace log output during
Terraform startup.

The goal here is that when someone opens a bug report, and includes the
trace log as our bug report template requests, we'll be able to see at a
glance which versions of these dependencies were involved, instead of
having to manually cross-reference in the go.mod file of the reported main
Terraform CLI version.

This does slightly grow the general overhead of the logs, but as long as
we keep this set of interesting dependencies relatively small it shouldn't
present any significant problem in typical usage.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/5ac1074c541f6e2dff4e05459764cf9f943168d3"}]

cty: The documented definition and comparison logic of cty.Number is now
refined to acknowledge that its true range is limited only to values
that have both a binary floating point and decimal representation,
because cty values are primarily designed to traverse JSON serialization
where numbers are always defined as decimal strings.

In particular, that means that two cty.Number values now always compare
as equal if their representation in JSON (under cty's own JSON encoder)
would be equal, even though the decimal approximation we use for that
conversion is slightly lossy. This pragmatic compromise avoids confusing
situations where a round-trip through JSON serialization (or other
serializations that use the same number format) may produce a value that
doesn't compare equal to the original.

This new definition of equals should not cause any significant behavior
change for any integer in our in-memory storage range, but may cause
some fractional values to compare equal where they didn't before if they
differ only by a small fraction.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/ca6d3cf50f5cf92f168069fa17846d6b5d0622ea"},{"sha":"858dc96859aeb1975703e8a2e290e2da807833c4","author":{"email":"711c73f64afdce07b7e38039a96d2224209e9a6c@chrisarcand.com","name":"Chris Arcand"},"message":"Merge pull request #29853 from hashicorp/cloud-tags-workspace

Fix typo in 0.13 upgrade guide","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/19101df1d4d04cab44d169b0177817ea711dc39b"},{"sha":"5ac1074c541f6e2dff4e05459764cf9f943168d3","author":{"email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk","name":"Martin Atkins"},"message":"main: Report version information for "interesting" dependencies

We have a few dependencies that are such a significant part of Terraform's
behavior that they will often be the root cause of or the solution to a
bug reported against Terraform.

As a small quality-of-life improvement to help with diagnosing those,
we'll now report the selected versions for each of these so-called
"interesting" dependencies as part of our initial trace log output during
Terraform startup.

The goal here is that when someone opens a bug report, and includes the
trace log as our bug report template requests, we'll be able to see at a
glance which versions of these dependencies were involved, instead of
having to manually cross-reference in the go.mod file of the reported main
Terraform CLI version.

This does slightly grow the general overhead of the logs, but as long as
we keep this set of interesting dependencies relatively small it shouldn't
present any significant problem in typical usage.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/5ac1074c541f6e2dff4e05459764cf9f943168d3"}]

cty: The documented definition and comparison logic of cty.Number is now
refined to acknowledge that its true range is limited only to values
that have both a binary floating point and decimal representation,
because cty values are primarily designed to traverse JSON serialization
where numbers are always defined as decimal strings.

In particular, that means that two cty.Number values now always compare
as equal if their representation in JSON (under cty's own JSON encoder)
would be equal, even though the decimal approximation we use for that
conversion is slightly lossy. This pragmatic compromise avoids confusing
situations where a round-trip through JSON serialization (or other
serializations that use the same number format) may produce a value that
doesn't compare equal to the original.

This new definition of equals should not cause any significant behavior
change for any integer in our in-memory storage range, but may cause
some fractional values to compare equal where they didn't before if they
differ only by a small fraction.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/ca6d3cf50f5cf92f168069fa17846d6b5d0622ea"},{"sha":"858dc96859aeb1975703e8a2e290e2da807833c4","author":{"email":"711c73f64afdce07b7e38039a96d2224209e9a6c@chrisarcand.com","name":"Chris Arcand"},"message":"Merge pull request #29853 from hashicorp/cloud-tags-workspace

cty: The documented definition and comparison logic of cty.Number is now
refined to acknowledge that its true range is limited only to values
that have both a binary floating point and decimal representation,
because cty values are primarily designed to traverse JSON serialization
where numbers are always defined as decimal strings.

In particular, that means that two cty.Number values now always compare
as equal if their representation in JSON (under cty's own JSON encoder)
would be equal, even though the decimal approximation we use for that
conversion is slightly lossy. This pragmatic compromise avoids confusing
situations where a round-trip through JSON serialization (or other
serializations that use the same number format) may produce a value that
doesn't compare equal to the original.

This new definition of equals should not cause any significant behavior
change for any integer in our in-memory storage range, but may cause
some fractional values to compare equal where they didn't before if they
differ only by a small fraction.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/ca6d3cf50f5cf92f168069fa17846d6b5d0622ea"},{"sha":"858dc96859aeb1975703e8a2e290e2da807833c4","author":{"email":"711c73f64afdce07b7e38039a96d2224209e9a6c@chrisarcand.com","name":"Chris Arcand"},"message":"Merge pull request #29853 from hashicorp/cloud-tags-workspace

Fix typo in 0.13 upgrade guide","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/19101df1d4d04cab44d169b0177817ea711dc39b"},{"sha":"5ac1074c541f6e2dff4e05459764cf9f943168d3","author":{"email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk","name":"Martin Atkins"},"message":"main: Report version information for "interesting" dependencies

We have a few dependencies that are such a significant part of Terraform's
behavior that they will often be the root cause of or the solution to a
bug reported against Terraform.

As a small quality-of-life improvement to help with diagnosing those,
we'll now report the selected versions for each of these so-called
"interesting" dependencies as part of our initial trace log output during
Terraform startup.

The goal here is that when someone opens a bug report, and includes the
trace log as our bug report template requests, we'll be able to see at a
glance which versions of these dependencies were involved, instead of
having to manually cross-reference in the go.mod file of the reported main
Terraform CLI version.

This does slightly grow the general overhead of the logs, but as long as
we keep this set of interesting dependencies relatively small it shouldn't
present any significant problem in typical usage.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/5ac1074c541f6e2dff4e05459764cf9f943168d3"}]

cty: The documented definition and comparison logic of cty.Number is now
refined to acknowledge that its true range is limited only to values
that have both a binary floating point and decimal representation,
because cty values are primarily designed to traverse JSON serialization
where numbers are always defined as decimal strings.

In particular, that means that two cty.Number values now always compare
as equal if their representation in JSON (under cty's own JSON encoder)
would be equal, even though the decimal approximation we use for that
conversion is slightly lossy. This pragmatic compromise avoids confusing
situations where a round-trip through JSON serialization (or other
serializations that use the same number format) may produce a value that
doesn't compare equal to the original.

This new definition of equals should not cause any significant behavior
change for any integer in our in-memory storage range, but may cause
some fractional values to compare equal where they didn't before if they
differ only by a small fraction.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/ca6d3cf50f5cf92f168069fa17846d6b5d0622ea"},{"sha":"858dc96859aeb1975703e8a2e290e2da807833c4","author":{"email":"711c73f64afdce07b7e38039a96d2224209e9a6c@chrisarcand.com","name":"Chris Arcand"},"message":"Merge pull request #29853 from hashicorp/cloud-tags-workspace

Fix typo in 0.13 upgrade guide","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/19101df1d4d04cab44d169b0177817ea711dc39b"},{"sha":"5ac1074c541f6e2dff4e05459764cf9f943168d3","author":{"email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk","name":"Martin Atkins"},"message":"main: Report version information for "interesting" dependencies

We have a few dependencies that are such a significant part of Terraform's
behavior that they will often be the root cause of or the solution to a
bug reported against Terraform.

As a small quality-of-life improvement to help with diagnosing those,
we'll now report the selected versions for each of these so-called
"interesting" dependencies as part of our initial trace log output during
Terraform startup.

The goal here is that when someone opens a bug report, and includes the
trace log as our bug report template requests, we'll be able to see at a
glance which versions of these dependencies were involved, instead of
having to manually cross-reference in the go.mod file of the reported main
Terraform CLI version.

This does slightly grow the general overhead of the logs, but as long as
we keep this set of interesting dependencies relatively small it shouldn't
present any significant problem in typical usage.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/5ac1074c541f6e2dff4e05459764cf9f943168d3"}]

We have a few dependencies that are such a significant part of Terraform's
behavior that they will often be the root cause of or the solution to a
bug reported against Terraform.

As a small quality-of-life improvement to help with diagnosing those,
we'll now report the selected versions for each of these so-called
"interesting" dependencies as part of our initial trace log output during
Terraform startup.

The goal here is that when someone opens a bug report, and includes the
trace log as our bug report template requests, we'll be able to see at a
glance which versions of these dependencies were involved, instead of
having to manually cross-reference in the go.mod file of the reported main
Terraform CLI version.

This does slightly grow the general overhead of the logs, but as long as
we keep this set of interesting dependencies relatively small it shouldn't
present any significant problem in typical usage.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/5ac1074c541f6e2dff4e05459764cf9f943168d3"}]

cty: The documented definition and comparison logic of cty.Number is now
refined to acknowledge that its true range is limited only to values
that have both a binary floating point and decimal representation,
because cty values are primarily designed to traverse JSON serialization
where numbers are always defined as decimal strings.

In particular, that means that two cty.Number values now always compare
as equal if their representation in JSON (under cty's own JSON encoder)
would be equal, even though the decimal approximation we use for that
conversion is slightly lossy. This pragmatic compromise avoids confusing
situations where a round-trip through JSON serialization (or other
serializations that use the same number format) may produce a value that
doesn't compare equal to the original.

This new definition of equals should not cause any significant behavior
change for any integer in our in-memory storage range, but may cause
some fractional values to compare equal where they didn't before if they
differ only by a small fraction.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/ca6d3cf50f5cf92f168069fa17846d6b5d0622ea"},{"sha":"858dc96859aeb1975703e8a2e290e2da807833c4","author":{"email":"711c73f64afdce07b7e38039a96d2224209e9a6c@chrisarcand.com","name":"Chris Arcand"},"message":"Merge pull request #29853 from hashicorp/cloud-tags-workspace

Fix typo in 0.13 upgrade guide","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/19101df1d4d04cab44d169b0177817ea711dc39b"},{"sha":"5ac1074c541f6e2dff4e05459764cf9f943168d3","author":{"email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk","name":"Martin Atkins"},"message":"main: Report version information for "interesting" dependencies

We have a few dependencies that are such a significant part of Terraform's
behavior that they will often be the root cause of or the solution to a
bug reported against Terraform.

As a small quality-of-life improvement to help with diagnosing those,
we'll now report the selected versions for each of these so-called
"interesting" dependencies as part of our initial trace log output during
Terraform startup.

The goal here is that when someone opens a bug report, and includes the
trace log as our bug report template requests, we'll be able to see at a
glance which versions of these dependencies were involved, instead of
having to manually cross-reference in the go.mod file of the reported main
Terraform CLI version.

This does slightly grow the general overhead of the logs, but as long as
we keep this set of interesting dependencies relatively small it shouldn't
present any significant problem in typical usage.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/5ac1074c541f6e2dff4e05459764cf9f943168d3"}]

cty: The documented definition and comparison logic of cty.Number is now
refined to acknowledge that its true range is limited only to values
that have both a binary floating point and decimal representation,
because cty values are primarily designed to traverse JSON serialization

We have a few dependencies that are such a significant part of Terraform's
behavior that they will often be the root cause of or the solution to a
bug reported against Terraform.

As a small quality-of-life improvement to help with diagnosing those,
we'll now report the selected versions for each of these so-called
"interesting" dependencies as part of our initial trace log output during
Terraform startup.

The goal here is that when someone opens a bug report, and includes the
trace log as our bug report template requests, we'll be able to see at a
glance which versions of these dependencies were involved, instead of
having to manually cross-reference in the go.mod file of the reported main
Terraform CLI version.

This does slightly grow the general overhead of the logs, but as long as
we keep this set of interesting dependencies relatively small it shouldn't
present any significant problem in typical usage.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/5ac1074c541f6e2dff4e05459764cf9f943168d3"}]

Fix typo in 0.13 upgrade guide","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/19101df1d4d04cab44d169b0177817ea711dc39b"},{"sha":"5ac1074c541f6e2dff4e05459764cf9f943168d3","author":{"email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk","name":"Martin Atkins"},"message":"main: Report version information for "interesting" dependencies

We have a few dependencies that are such a significant part of Terraform's
behavior that they will often be the root cause of or the solution to a
bug reported against Terraform.

As a small quality-of-life improvement to help with diagnosing those,
we'll now report the selected versions for each of these so-called
"interesting" dependencies as part of our initial trace log output during
Terraform startup.

The goal here is that when someone opens a bug report, and includes the
trace log as our bug report template requests, we'll be able to see at a
glance which versions of these dependencies were involved, instead of
having to manually cross-reference in the go.mod file of the reported main
Terraform CLI version.

This does slightly grow the general overhead of the logs, but as long as
we keep this set of interesting dependencies relatively small it shouldn't
present any significant problem in typical usage.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/5ac1074c541f6e2dff4e05459764cf9f943168d3"}]

Previously we ended up losing all of the error message detail produced by
the registry address parser, because we treated any registry address
failure as cause to parse the address as a go-getter-style remote address
instead.

That led to terrible feedback in the situation where the user _was_
trying to write a module address but it was invalid in some way.

Although we can't really tighten this up in the default case due to our
compatibility promises, it's never been valid to use the "version"
argument with anything other than a registry address and so as a
compromise here we'll use the presence of "version" as a heuristic for
user intent to parse the source address as a registry address, and thus
we can return a registry-address-specific error message in that case and
thus give more direct feedback about what was wrong.

This unfortunately won't help someone trying to install from the registry
_without_ a version constraint, but I didn't want to let perfect be the
enemy of the good here, particularly since we recommend using version
constraints with registry modules anyway; indeed, that's one of the main
benefits of using a registry rather than a remote source directly.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/ehud-eshet/terraform/commits/affe2c329561f40f13c0e94f4570321977527a77"},{"sha":"5facaf89702ec8e25e9f3a0b78b9f00139945fb4","author":{"email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com","name":"James Bardin"},"message":"update hcl@v2.11.0","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/ehud-eshet/terraform/commits/5facaf89702ec8e25e9f3a0b78b9f00139945fb4"},{"sha":"d8a127994cff54690263b02ead059ff61c92d0ce","author":{"email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com","name":"James Bardin"},"message":"Merge pull request #30056 from hashicorp/jbardin/update-hcl

When terraform detects that a user has no workspaces that map to their current configuration, it will prompt the user to create a new workspace and enter a value name. If the user ignores the prompt and exits it, the legacy backend (terraform.tfstate) will be left in a awkward state:

1. This saved backend config will show a diff for the JSON attributes "serial", "tags" and "hash"
2. "Terraform workspace list" will show an empty list
3. "Terraform apply" will run successfully using the previous workspace, from the previous config, not the one from the current saved backend config
4. The cloud config is not reflective of the current working directory

Solution: If the user exits the prompt, the saved backend config should not be updated because they did not select a new workspace. The Eigen commit changes the visibility of the `Packet` type ( `Packet4h2`) for the `Eigen::half` datatype. Prior to the commit, `Packet` type is defined as `Packet4h2` during both the `host` and `device` compile phases of hipcc/nvcc. After the commit the `Packet` type is defined as `Eigen::half` (size == 2) in the `host` compile phase, and as `Packet4h2` (size == 8) in the device compile phase.

`struct AvgPoolMeanReducer` has a member of type `Packet`(https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/r2.7/tensorflow/core/kernels/eigen_pooling.h#L367), and hence its size will be different during the `host` compile phase and `device` compile phase. It also seems that the implementation of the `average pooling` op ( https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/r2.7/tensorflow/core/kernels/avgpooling_op.h#L34-L38 ) will result in a `struct AvgPoolMeanReducer` argument being passed across the `host` / `device` compile boundary (atleast for `hipcc`) and size mismatch between the two, leads to the subsequent segfault.

The fix here is to ensure the `Packet` has the same definitition for both the `host` and `device` compile phases. However changing the type `packetCount_` to `int` unconditionally leads to compile errors, because during the non-gpu / gcc compiles the code within the `!defined(__HIPCC__)` block gets activated, and hence the changes in this commit are guarded by `defined(__HIPCC__)`. Using `int` for `packetCount_` is ok because `PacketAcces`s is already set to `false` within (a different) `defined(__HIPCC__)` block.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/qingyunqu/tensorflow/commits/eae91a24e179bc4d279ef1fe86d6050f30154215"},{"sha":"9e2237ee604e8a86f379f2d2236f1772491812c8","author":{"email":"88687f8e9d306a57b2163982d4c8fc9f4a2c5ea6@gmail.com","name":"Jacky_Yin"},"message":"fix: GIT_REPOSITORY for eigen

In `tf.math`, `unsorted_segment_max`, `unsorted_segment_mean`, `unsorted_segment_min`, `unsorted_segment_prod`, `unsorted_segment_sqrt_n` and `unsorted_segment_sum` all expect that `segments_ids` are less than `num_segments`. On CPU, these are validated, and an error is thrown for out-of-bounds indices. On Gpu, these are NOT validated, and out-of-bound indices do not throw an error but instead result in safe but unspecified behavior.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 415059438
Change-Id: I6aaed7232ef50631416055328cec9984130ce496","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/106ff4e41f4574a670499a43ecfdf0ccacc1ffe7"},{"sha":"54441d239c4103f36c0080d1a6ac83e1e06f942b","author":{"email":"3597b8ab71b66d46ec439caf0c075cd0b82fcc57@google.com","name":"Katherine Wu"},"message":"Cache the results of list_children when exporting SavedModel, and trigger function side effects before gathering the children.

As part of the SavedModel layering project, `Trackable` will have a single function that returns all Trackable children -- functions included. That means that the following will be combined into a single function:
- `_checkpoint_dependencies`
- `_list_extra_dependencies_for_serialization`
- `_list_functions_for_serialization`

Currently, SavedModel caches the result to `_list_functions_for_serialization`, but not for the other methods. Why? Because the functions returned from `_list_functions_for_serialization` can trigger side effects when tracing (such as adding a variable to the `Trackable`).

We need to keep the guarantee that children are only gathered a single time, because in many cases (such as the `Resource` class), new tf.functions are generated each time. In `Resource`, a new init/create/destroy function is generated inside `_list_functions_for_serialization`.

Therefore, SavedModel saving must cache the results to `list_children`, while at the same time triggering the function tracing and side effects in the appropriate manner.

Added an example and updated format","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/f7acf713467db5454d08ec24cdc7a1c3dc8e0d88"},{"sha":"54441d239c4103f36c0080d1a6ac83e1e06f942b","author":{"email":"3597b8ab71b66d46ec439caf0c075cd0b82fcc57@google.com","name":"Katherine Wu"},"message":"Cache the results of list_children when exporting SavedModel, and trigger function side effects before gathering the children.

As part of the SavedModel layering project, `Trackable` will have a single function that returns all Trackable children -- functions included. That means that the following will be combined into a single function:
- `_checkpoint_dependencies`
- `_list_extra_dependencies_for_serialization`
- `_list_functions_for_serialization`

Currently, SavedModel caches the result to `_list_functions_for_serialization`, but not for the other methods. Why? Because the functions returned from `_list_functions_for_serialization` can trigger side effects when tracing (such as adding a variable to the `Trackable`).

We need to keep the guarantee that children are only gathered a single time, because in many cases (such as the `Resource` class), new tf.functions are generated each time. In `Resource`, a new init/create/destroy function is generated inside `_list_functions_for_serialization`.

Therefore, SavedModel saving must cache the results to `list_children`, while at the same time triggering the function tracing and side effects in the appropriate manner.

Gather op should get indices as constant and not as upper/lower bound as the default implementation does. Getting only the upper bound with fetch a particular value from data at the lowest or the highest index which is incorrect.

For example,

data = [3, 2]
indices = sort([0, 1])

Getting the upper bound on indices will return [1, 1], making the gather result bound [2, 2] and not [3, 2].

Added an example and updated format","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/smalltalkman/tensorflow/commits/f7acf713467db5454d08ec24cdc7a1c3dc8e0d88"},{"sha":"54441d239c4103f36c0080d1a6ac83e1e06f942b","author":{"email":"3597b8ab71b66d46ec439caf0c075cd0b82fcc57@google.com","name":"Katherine Wu"},"message":"Cache the results of list_children when exporting SavedModel, and trigger function side effects before gathering the children.

As part of the SavedModel layering project, `Trackable` will have a single function that returns all Trackable children -- functions included. That means that the following will be combined into a single function:
- `_checkpoint_dependencies`
- `_list_extra_dependencies_for_serialization`
- `_list_functions_for_serialization`

Currently, SavedModel caches the result to `_list_functions_for_serialization`, but not for the other methods. Why? Because the functions returned from `_list_functions_for_serialization` can trigger side effects when tracing (such as adding a variable to the `Trackable`).

We need to keep the guarantee that children are only gathered a single time, because in many cases (such as the `Resource` class), new tf.functions are generated each time. In `Resource`, a new init/create/destroy function is generated inside `_list_functions_for_serialization`.

Therefore, SavedModel saving must cache the results to `list_children`, while at the same time triggering the function tracing and side effects in the appropriate manner.

Added an example and updated format","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/TheRakeshPurohit/tensorflow/commits/f7acf713467db5454d08ec24cdc7a1c3dc8e0d88"},{"sha":"54441d239c4103f36c0080d1a6ac83e1e06f942b","author":{"email":"3597b8ab71b66d46ec439caf0c075cd0b82fcc57@google.com","name":"Katherine Wu"},"message":"Cache the results of list_children when exporting SavedModel, and trigger function side effects before gathering the children.

As part of the SavedModel layering project, `Trackable` will have a single function that returns all Trackable children -- functions included. That means that the following will be combined into a single function:
- `_checkpoint_dependencies`
- `_list_extra_dependencies_for_serialization`
- `_list_functions_for_serialization`

Currently, SavedModel caches the result to `_list_functions_for_serialization`, but not for the other methods. Why? Because the functions returned from `_list_functions_for_serialization` can trigger side effects when tracing (such as adding a variable to the `Trackable`).

We need to keep the guarantee that children are only gathered a single time, because in many cases (such as the `Resource` class), new tf.functions are generated each time. In `Resource`, a new init/create/destroy function is generated inside `_list_functions_for_serialization`.

Therefore, SavedModel saving must cache the results to `list_children`, while at the same time triggering the function tracing and side effects in the appropriate manner.

* dnn: LSTM optimisation

This uses the AVX-optimised fastGEMM1T for matrix multiplications where available, instead of the standard cv::gemm.

fastGEMM1T is already used by the fully-connected layer.  This commit involves two minor modifications:
 - Use unaligned access.  I don't believe this involves any performance hit in on modern CPUs (Nehalem and Bulldozer onwards) in the case where the address is actually aligned.
 - Allow for weight matrices where the number of columns is not a multiple of 8.

I have not enabled AVX-512 as I don't have an AVX-512 CPU to test on.

* Fix warning about initialisation order

* Remove C++11 syntax

* Fix build when AVX(2) is not available

In this case the CV_TRY_X macros are defined to 0, rather than being undefined.

* Minor changes as requested:

 - Don't check hardware support for AVX(2) when dispatch is disabled for these
 - Add braces

* Fix out-of-bounds access in fully connected layer

The old tail handling in fastGEMM1T implicitly rounded vecsize up to the next multiple of 8, and the fully connected layer implements padding up to the next multiple of 8 to cope with this.  The new tail handling does not round the vecsize upwards like this but it does require that the vecsize is at least 8.  To adapt to the new tail handling, the fully connected layer now rounds vecsize itself at the same time as adding the padding(which makes more sense anyway).

This also means that the fully connected layer always passes a vecsize of at least 8 to fastGEMM1T, which fixes the out-of-bounds access problems.

* Improve tail mask handling

 - Use static array for generating tail masks (as requested)
 - Apply tail mask to the weights as well as the input vectors to prevent spurious propagation of NaNs/Infs

* Revert whitespace change

* Improve readability of conditions for using AVX

* dnn(lstm): minor coding style changes, replaced left aligned cty: The documented definition and comparison logic of cty.Number is now
refined to acknowledge that its true range is limited only to values
that have both a binary floating point and decimal representation,
because cty values are primarily designed to traverse JSON serialization
where numbers are always defined as decimal strings.

In particular, that means that two cty.Number values now always compare
as equal if their representation in JSON (under cty's own JSON encoder)
would be equal, even though the decimal approximation we use for that
conversion is slightly lossy. This pragmatic compromise avoids confusing
situations where a round-trip through JSON serialization (or other
serializations that use the same number format) may produce a value that
doesn't compare equal to the original.

This new definition of equals should not cause any significant behavior
change for any integer in our in-memory storage range, but may cause
some fractional values to compare equal where they didn't before if they
differ only by a small fraction.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/ca6d3cf50f5cf92f168069fa17846d6b5d0622ea"},{"sha":"858dc96859aeb1975703e8a2e290e2da807833c4","author":{"email":"711c73f64afdce07b7e38039a96d2224209e9a6c@chrisarcand.com","name":"Chris Arcand"},"message":"Merge pull request #29853 from hashicorp/cloud-tags-workspace

We have a few dependencies that are such a significant part of Terraform's
behavior that they will often be the root cause of or the solution to a
bug reported against Terraform.

As a small quality-of-life improvement to help with diagnosing those,
we'll now report the selected versions for each of these so-called
"interesting" dependencies as part of our initial trace log output during
Terraform startup.

The goal here is that when someone opens a bug report, and includes the
trace log as our bug report template requests, we'll be able to see at a
glance which versions of these dependencies were involved, instead of
having to manually cross-reference in the go.mod file of the reported main
Terraform CLI version.

we keep this set of interesting dependencies relatively small it shouldn't
present any significant problem in typical usage.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/5ac1074c541f6e2dff4e05459764cf9f943168d3"}]

cty: The documented definition and comparison logic of cty.Number is now
refined to acknowledge that its true range is limited only to values
that have both a binary floating point and decimal representation,
because cty values are primarily designed to traverse JSON serialization
where numbers are always defined as decimal strings.

In particular, that means that two cty.Number values now always compare
as equal if their representation in JSON (under cty's own JSON encoder)
would be equal, even though the decimal approximation we use for that
conversion is slightly lossy. This pragmatic compromise avoids confusing
situations where a round-trip through JSON serialization (or other
serializations that use the same number format) may produce a value that
doesn't compare equal to the original.

This new definition of equals should not cause any significant behavior
change for any integer in our in-memory storage range, but may cause
some fractional values to compare equal where they didn't before if they
differ only by a small fraction.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/ca6d3cf50f5cf92f168069fa17846d6b5d0622ea"},{"sha":"858dc96859aeb1975703e8a2e290e2da807833c4","author":{"email":"711c73f64afdce07b7e38039a96d2224209e9a6c@chrisarcand.com","name":"Chris Arcand"},"message":"Merge pull request #29853 from hashicorp/cloud-tags-workspace

As a small quality-of-life improvement to help with diagnosing those,
we'll now report the selected versions for each of these so-called
"interesting" dependencies as part of our initial trace log output during
Terraform startup.

The goal here is that when someone opens a bug report, and includes the
trace log as our bug report template requests, we'll be able to see at a
glance which versions of these dependencies were involved, instead of
having to manually cross-reference in the go.mod file of the reported main
Terraform CLI version.

This does slightly grow the general overhead of the logs, but as long as
we keep this set of interesting dependencies relatively small it shouldn't
present any significant problem in typical usage.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/5ac1074c541f6e2dff4e05459764cf9f943168d3"}]

cty: The documented definition and comparison logic of cty.Number is now
refined to acknowledge that its true range is limited only to values
that have both a binary floating point and decimal representation,
because cty values are primarily designed to traverse JSON serialization
where numbers are always defined as decimal strings.

In particular, that means that two cty.Number values now always compare
as equal if their representation in JSON (under cty's own JSON encoder)
would be equal, even though the decimal approximation we use for that
conversion is slightly lossy. This pragmatic compromise avoids confusing
situations where a round-trip through JSON serialization (or other
serializations that use the same number format) may produce a value that
doesn't compare equal to the original.

This new definition of equals should not cause any significant behavior
change for any integer in our in-memory storage range, but may cause
some fractional values to compare equal where they didn't before if they
differ only by a small fraction.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/ca6d3cf50f5cf92f168069fa17846d6b5d0622ea"},{"sha":"858dc96859aeb1975703e8a2e290e2da807833c4","author":{"email":"711c73f64afdce07b7e38039a96d2224209e9a6c@chrisarcand.com","name":"Chris Arcand"},"message":"Merge pull request #29853 from hashicorp/cloud-tags-workspace

Fix typo in 0.13 upgrade guide","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/19101df1d4d04cab44d169b0177817ea711dc39b"},{"sha":"5ac1074c541f6e2dff4e05459764cf9f943168d3","author":{"email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk","name":"Martin Atkins"},"message":"main: Report version information for "interesting" dependencies

We have a few dependencies that are such a significant part of Terraform's
behavior that they will often be the root cause of or the solution to a
bug reported against Terraform.

As a small quality-of-life improvement to help with diagnosing those,
we'll now report the selected versions for each of these so-called
"interesting" dependencies as part of our initial trace log output during
Terraform startup.

The goal here is that when someone opens a bug report, and includes the
trace log as our bug report template requests, we'll be able to see at a
glance which versions of these dependencies were involved, instead of
having to manually cross-reference in the go.mod file of the reported main
Terraform CLI version.

This does slightly grow the general overhead of the logs, but as long as
we keep this set of interesting dependencies relatively small it shouldn't
present any significant problem in typical usage.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/5ac1074c541f6e2dff4e05459764cf9f943168d3"}]

cty: The documented definition and comparison logic of cty.Number is now
refined to acknowledge that its true range is limited only to values
that have both a binary floating point and decimal representation,
because cty values are primarily designed to traverse JSON serialization
where numbers are always defined as decimal strings.

In particular, that means that two cty.Number values now always compare
as equal if their representation in JSON (under cty's own JSON encoder)
would be equal, even though the decimal approximation we use for that
conversion is slightly lossy. This pragmatic compromise avoids confusing
situations where a round-trip through JSON serialization (or other
serializations that use the same number format) may produce a value that
doesn't compare equal to the original.

This new definition of equals should not cause any significant behavior
change for any integer in our in-memory storage range, but may cause
some fractional values to compare equal where they didn't before if they
differ only by a small fraction.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/ca6d3cf50f5cf92f168069fa17846d6b5d0622ea"},{"sha":"858dc96859aeb1975703e8a2e290e2da807833c4","author":{"email":"711c73f64afdce07b7e38039a96d2224209e9a6c@chrisarcand.com","name":"Chris Arcand"},"message":"Merge pull request #29853 from hashicorp/cloud-tags-workspace

We have a few dependencies that are such a significant part of Terraform's
behavior that they will often be the root cause of or the solution to a
bug reported against Terraform.

As a small quality-of-life improvement to help with diagnosing those,
we'll now report the selected versions for each of these so-called
"interesting" dependencies as part of our initial trace log output during
Terraform startup.

The goal here is that when someone opens a bug report, and includes the
trace log as our bug report template requests, we'll be able to see at a
glance which versions of these dependencies were involved, instead of
having to manually cross-reference in the go.mod file of the reported main
Terraform CLI version.

This does slightly grow the general overhead of the logs, but as long as
we keep this set of interesting dependencies relatively small it shouldn't
present any significant problem in typical usage.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/5ac1074c541f6e2dff4e05459764cf9f943168d3"}]

Fix typo in 0.13 upgrade guide","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/19101df1d4d04cab44d169b0177817ea711dc39b"},{"sha":"5ac1074c541f6e2dff4e05459764cf9f943168d3","author":{"email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk","name":"Martin Atkins"},"message":"main: Report version information for "interesting" dependencies

We have a few dependencies that are such a significant part of Terraform's
behavior that they will often be the root cause of or the solution to a
bug reported against Terraform.

As a small quality-of-life improvement to help with diagnosing those,
we'll now report the selected versions for each of these so-called
"interesting" dependencies as part of our initial trace log output during
Terraform startup.

The goal here is that when someone opens a bug report, and includes the
trace log as our bug report template requests, we'll be able to see at a
glance which versions of these dependencies were involved, instead of
having to manually cross-reference in the go.mod file of the reported main
Terraform CLI version.

This does slightly grow the general overhead of the logs, but as long as
we keep this set of interesting dependencies relatively small it shouldn't
present any significant problem in typical usage.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/5ac1074c541f6e2dff4e05459764cf9f943168d3"}]

[{"sha":"f521ba6cd747d8c44b35c3c2b22082e01357c756","author":{"email":"711c73f64afdce07b7e38039a96d2224209e9a6c@chrisarcand.com","name":"Chris Arcand"},"message":"Remove 'enhanced' backend type distinction

Cloud/Enterprise's), has been found to be a confusing vestige which need

directly to their primary purpose, which is storage of state snapshots

cty: The documented definition and comparison logic of cty.Number is now
refined to acknowledge that its true range is limited only to values
that have both a binary floating point and decimal representation,
because cty values are primarily designed to traverse JSON serialization
where numbers are always defined as decimal strings.

In particular, that means that two cty.Number values now always compare
as equal if their representation in JSON (under cty's own JSON encoder)
would be equal, even though the decimal approximation we use for that
conversion is slightly lossy. This pragmatic compromise avoids confusing
situations where a round-trip through JSON serialization (or other
serializations that use the same number format) may produce a value that
doesn't compare equal to the original.

This new definition of equals should not cause any significant behavior
change for any integer in our in-memory storage range, but may cause
some fractional values to compare equal where they didn't before if they

Fix typo in 0.13 upgrade guide","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/19101df1d4d04cab44d169b0177817ea711dc39b"},{"sha":"5ac1074c541f6e2dff4e05459764cf9f943168d3","author":{"email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk","name":"Martin Atkins"},"message":"main: Report version information for "interesting" dependencies

We have a few dependencies that are such a significant part of Terraform's
behavior that they will often be the root cause of or the solution to a
bug reported against Terraform.

As a small quality-of-life improvement to help with diagnosing those,
we'll now report the selected versions for each of these so-called
"interesting" dependencies as part of our initial trace log output during
Terraform startup.

The goal here is that when someone opens a bug report, and includes the
trace log as our bug report template requests, we'll be able to see at a
glance which versions of these dependencies were involved, instead of
having to manually cross-reference in the go.mod file of the reported main
Terraform CLI version.

This does slightly grow the general overhead of the logs, but as long as
we keep this set of interesting dependencies relatively small it shouldn't
present any significant problem in typical usage.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/5ac1074c541f6e2dff4e05459764cf9f943168d3"}]

'pattern' prompt should work just fine - but because their workspaces
are already present in TFC, the 'migration' here is really just
realigning their local workspaces with Terraform Cloud. Instead of
forcing users to do the mental gymnastics of what it means to migrate
from 'prefix' - and because their remote workspaces probably already exist and
already conform to Terraform Cloud's naming concerns - streamline the
process for them and calculate the necessary pattern to migrate as-is,

Fix typo in 0.13 upgrade guide","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/19101df1d4d04cab44d169b0177817ea711dc39b"},{"sha":"5ac1074c541f6e2dff4e05459764cf9f943168d3","author":{"email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk","name":"Martin Atkins"},"message":"main: Report version information for "interesting" dependencies

We have a few dependencies that are such a significant part of Terraform's
behavior that they will often be the root cause of or the solution to a
bug reported against Terraform.

As a small quality-of-life improvement to help with diagnosing those,
we'll now report the selected versions for each of these so-called
"interesting" dependencies as part of our initial trace log output during
Terraform startup.

The goal here is that when someone opens a bug report, and includes the
trace log as our bug report template requests, we'll be able to see at a
glance which versions of these dependencies were involved, instead of
having to manually cross-reference in the go.mod file of the reported main
Terraform CLI version.

This does slightly grow the general overhead of the logs, but as long as
we keep this set of interesting dependencies relatively small it shouldn't
present any significant problem in typical usage.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/5ac1074c541f6e2dff4e05459764cf9f943168d3"}]

Gather op should get indices as constant and not as upper/lower bound as the default implementation does. Getting only the upper bound with fetch a particular value from data at the lowest or the highest index which is incorrect.

For example,

indices = sort([0, 1])

Getting the upper bound on indices will return [1, 1], making the gather result bound [2, 2] and not [3, 2].

[{"sha":"ad607469c58d337d23d05e3be73087d370f7d715","author":{"email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com","name":"Brian Vaughn"},"message":"StyleX plug-in for resolving atomic styles to values for props.xstyle (#22808)

Adds the concept of "plugins" to the inspected element payload. Also adds the first plugin, one that resolves StyleX atomic style names to their values and displays them as a unified style object (rather than a nested array of objects and booleans).

Source file names are displayed first, in dim color, followed by an ordered set of resolved style values.

For builds with the new feature flag disabled, there is no observable change.

A next step to build on top of this could be to make the style values editable, but change the logic such that editing one directly added an inline style to the item (rather than modifying the stylex class– which may be shared between multiple other components).","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/SimenB/react/commits/ad607469c58d337d23d05e3be73087d370f7d715"}]

This PR does the following:

report and increase verbosity.
- Changes `struct ConversionParams.output_names` to `struct
ConversionParams.input_output_names` to be more precise on the actual use of

ops

and it was causing some confusion.  Now the knowledge of what bugs exist at
particular cuDNN versions lives entirely in stream_executor, and callers just
specify whether cuDNN frontend should be preferred when it works.

This also results in enabling cuDNN frontend for identity-activation fused
convs in XLA, which were previously disabled.

Adds the concept of "plugins" to the inspected element payload. Also adds the first plugin, one that resolves StyleX atomic style names to their values and displays them as a unified style object (rather than a nested array of objects and booleans).

Source file names are displayed first, in dim color, followed by an ordered set of resolved style values.

For builds with the new feature flag disabled, there is no observable change.

A next step to build on top of this could be to make the style values editable, but change the logic such that editing one directly added an inline style to the item (rather than modifying the stylex class– which may be shared between multiple other components).","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/salazarm/react/commits/ad607469c58d337d23d05e3be73087d370f7d715"},{"sha":"06f403481fe1f30d6952ad60ecd759b410962926","author":{"email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io","name":"Andrew Clark"},"message":"Add CI job to check npm dependencies (#22881)

[{"sha":"f521ba6cd747d8c44b35c3c2b22082e01357c756","author":{"email":"711c73f64afdce07b7e38039a96d2224209e9a6c@chrisarcand.com","name":"Chris Arcand"},"message":"Remove 'enhanced' backend type distinction

As explained in the changes: The 'enhanced' backend terminology, which
only truly pertains to the 'remote' backend with a single API (Terraform
Cloud/Enterprise's), has been found to be a confusing vestige which need
only be explained in the context of the 'remote' backend.

[{"sha":"54441d239c4103f36c0080d1a6ac83e1e06f942b","author":{"email":"3597b8ab71b66d46ec439caf0c075cd0b82fcc57@google.com","name":"Katherine Wu"},"message":"Cache the results of list_children when exporting SavedModel, and trigger function side effects before gathering the children.

As part of the SavedModel layering project, `Trackable` will have a single function that returns all Trackable children -- functions included. That means that the following will be combined into a single function:
- `_checkpoint_dependencies`
- `_list_extra_dependencies_for_serialization`
- `_list_functions_for_serialization`

Currently, SavedModel caches the result to `_list_functions_for_serialization`, but not for the other methods. Why? Because the functions returned from `_list_functions_for_serialization` can trigger side effects when tracing (such as adding a variable to the `Trackable`).

We need to keep the guarantee that children are only gathered a single time, because in many cases (such as the `Resource` class), new tf.functions are generated each time. In `Resource`, a new init/create/destroy function is generated inside `_list_functions_for_serialization`.

Therefore, SavedModel saving must cache the results to `list_children`, while at the same time triggering the function tracing and side effects in the appropriate manner.

Change-Id: Ie96925327e8f91cd973751a599f18af66636adcd","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/clayne/tensorflow/commits/005ddfe4a123d7471030065f73d4fade10cc2775"},{"sha":"41ad65049b13213b6119b7d07a264e2b2661c72b","author":{"email":"d2f798c68dab979d539dfeddebc6b96a78f505a8@google.com","name":"Edward Schwartz"},"message":"Add caution to math.unsorted_segment_* documentation about bad segment_ids on GPU

In `tf.math`, `unsorted_segment_max`, `unsorted_segment_mean`, `unsorted_segment_min`, `unsorted_segment_prod`, `unsorted_segment_sqrt_n` and `unsorted_segment_sum` all expect that `segments_ids` are less than `num_segments`. On CPU, these are validated, and an error is thrown for out-of-bounds indices. On Gpu, these are NOT validated, and out-of-bound indices do not throw an error but instead result in safe but unspecified behavior.

Unique TensorFlower"},"message":"Reject input with dynamic shapes in Squeeze xla op kernel

Bounded dynamic dimensions may have size one at runtime and therefore the rank of the output is not known at the compile time. XLA doesn't support shapes with unknown rank so we need to reject such inputs.

Originally the kernel would have been implemented assuming the static input shapes and wasn't updated with bounded dynamic shapes.

cty: The documented definition and comparison logic of cty.Number is now
refined to acknowledge that its true range is limited only to values
that have both a binary floating point and decimal representation,
because cty values are primarily designed to traverse JSON serialization
where numbers are always defined as decimal strings.

In particular, that means that two cty.Number values now always compare
as equal if their representation in JSON (under cty's own JSON encoder)
would be equal, even though the decimal approximation we use for that
conversion is slightly lossy. This pragmatic compromise avoids confusing
situations where a round-trip through JSON serialization (or other
serializations that use the same number format) may produce a value that
doesn't compare equal to the original.

This new definition of equals should not cause any significant behavior
change for any integer in our in-memory storage range, but may cause
some fractional values to compare equal where they didn't before if they
differ only by a small fraction.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/ca6d3cf50f5cf92f168069fa17846d6b5d0622ea"},{"sha":"858dc96859aeb1975703e8a2e290e2da807833c4","author":{"email":"711c73f64afdce07b7e38039a96d2224209e9a6c@chrisarcand.com","name":"Chris Arcand"},"message":"Merge pull request #29853 from hashicorp/cloud-tags-workspace

Fix typo in 0.13 upgrade guide","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/19101df1d4d04cab44d169b0177817ea711dc39b"},{"sha":"5ac1074c541f6e2dff4e05459764cf9f943168d3","author":{"email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk","name":"Martin Atkins"},"message":"main: Report version information for "interesting" dependencies

We have a few dependencies that are such a significant part of Terraform's
behavior that they will often be the root cause of or the solution to a
bug reported against Terraform.

As a small quality-of-life improvement to help with diagnosing those,
we'll now report the selected versions for each of these so-called
"interesting" dependencies as part of our initial trace log output during
Terraform startup.

The goal here is that when someone opens a bug report, and includes the
trace log as our bug report template requests, we'll be able to see at a
glance which versions of these dependencies were involved, instead of
having to manually cross-reference in the go.mod file of the reported main
Terraform CLI version.

This does slightly grow the general overhead of the logs, but as long as
we keep this set of interesting dependencies relatively small it shouldn't
present any significant problem in typical usage.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/5ac1074c541f6e2dff4e05459764cf9f943168d3"}]

PiperOrigin-RevId: 415059438
Change-Id: I6aaed7232ef50631416055328cec9984130ce496","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Nexuscompute/tensorflow/commits/106ff4e41f4574a670499a43ecfdf0ccacc1ffe7"},{"sha":"54441d239c4103f36c0080d1a6ac83e1e06f942b","author":{"email":"3597b8ab71b66d46ec439caf0c075cd0b82fcc57@google.com","name":"Katherine Wu"},"message":"Cache the results of list_children when exporting SavedModel, and trigger function side effects before gathering the children.

As part of the SavedModel layering project, `Trackable` will have a single function that returns all Trackable children -- functions included. That means that the following will be combined into a single function:
- `_checkpoint_dependencies`
- `_list_extra_dependencies_for_serialization`
- `_list_functions_for_serialization`

Currently, SavedModel caches the result to `_list_functions_for_serialization`, but not for the other methods. Why? Because the functions returned from `_list_functions_for_serialization` can trigger side effects when tracing (such as adding a variable to the `Trackable`).

We need to keep the guarantee that children are only gathered a single time, because in many cases (such as the `Resource` class), new tf.functions are generated each time. In `Resource`, a new init/create/destroy function is generated inside `_list_functions_for_serialization`.

Therefore, SavedModel saving must cache the results to `list_children`, while at the same time triggering the function tracing and side effects in the appropriate manner.

cty: The documented definition and comparison logic of cty.Number is now
refined to acknowledge that its true range is limited only to values
that have both a binary floating point and decimal representation,
because cty values are primarily designed to traverse JSON serialization
where numbers are always defined as decimal strings.

In particular, that means that two cty.Number values now always compare
as equal if their representation in JSON (under cty's own JSON encoder)
would be equal, even though the decimal approximation we use for that
conversion is slightly lossy. This pragmatic compromise avoids confusing
situations where a round-trip through JSON serialization (or other
serializations that use the same number format) may produce a value that
doesn't compare equal to the original.

This new definition of equals should not cause any significant behavior
change for any integer in our in-memory storage range, but may cause
some fractional values to compare equal where they didn't before if they
differ only by a small fraction.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/ca6d3cf50f5cf92f168069fa17846d6b5d0622ea"},{"sha":"858dc96859aeb1975703e8a2e290e2da807833c4","author":{"email":"711c73f64afdce07b7e38039a96d2224209e9a6c@chrisarcand.com","name":"Chris Arcand"},"message":"Merge pull request #29853 from hashicorp/cloud-tags-workspace

We have a few dependencies that are such a significant part of Terraform's
behavior that they will often be the root cause of or the solution to a
bug reported against Terraform.

As a small quality-of-life improvement to help with diagnosing those,
we'll now report the selected versions for each of these so-called
"interesting" dependencies as part of our initial trace log output during
Terraform startup.

The goal here is that when someone opens a bug report, and includes the
trace log as our bug report template requests, we'll be able to see at a
glance which versions of these dependencies were involved, instead of
having to manually cross-reference in the go.mod file of the reported main
Terraform CLI version.

This does slightly grow the general overhead of the logs, but as long as
we keep this set of interesting dependencies relatively small it shouldn't
present any significant problem in typical usage.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/5ac1074c541f6e2dff4e05459764cf9f943168d3"}]

cty: The documented definition and comparison logic of cty.Number is now
refined to acknowledge that its true range is limited only to values
that have both a binary floating point and decimal representation,
because cty values are primarily designed to traverse JSON serialization
where numbers are always defined as decimal strings.

In particular, that means that two cty.Number values now always compare
as equal if their representation in JSON (under cty's own JSON encoder)
would be equal, even though the decimal approximation we use for that
conversion is slightly lossy. This pragmatic compromise avoids confusing
situations where a round-trip through JSON serialization (or other
serializations that use the same number format) may produce a value that
doesn't compare equal to the original.

This new definition of equals should not cause any significant behavior
change for any integer in our in-memory storage range, but may cause
some fractional values to compare equal where they didn't before if they
differ only by a small fraction.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/ca6d3cf50f5cf92f168069fa17846d6b5d0622ea"},{"sha":"858dc96859aeb1975703e8a2e290e2da807833c4","author":{"email":"711c73f64afdce07b7e38039a96d2224209e9a6c@chrisarcand.com","name":"Chris Arcand"},"message":"Merge pull request #29853 from hashicorp/cloud-tags-workspace
